al concerns such as her difficult relationships with her mother and her husband. Taken together, these letters are a testament both to an individual woman and to enduring feminist concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAuthors, Latin (Medieval and modern)zItalyvCorrespondence. 0aFeministszItalyvCorrespondence. 0aHumanistszItalyvCorrespondence. 0aWomenzItalyxHistoryyRenaissance, 1450-1600vSources. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aRobin, Diana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226721583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226721583.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles